############### Normal Workflow
# pull any changes from remote master branch, (if you want to keep local files and merge manually use git fetch)
git pull origin master

# create a new branch and switch to it
git checkout -b 20250724

# after you've made changes 
git status

# add them to branch and commit with msg
git commit -am <msg>

# push changes back to remote
git push --set-upstream origin 20250724
git push origin master

############### Switch branch
git checkout <branchname>

############### Create new branch and switch
git checkout -b <branch>

############### Discard local changes
git reset --hard

############### Files are not being deleted even if in .gitignore
git rm --cached <file>
git commit -m "cleaning up repo"
git push origin master

############### Idea - Main point
You make your normal changes to your file
Then you either add or remove those files from your commit (git add or git rm)
then you commit changes
then you push back to the origin
